          "body": "Numbers 14 opens with the catastrophic aftermath of the spies' report. The congregation wept all night (14:1), grumbled against Moses and Aaron (14:2), and moved from complaint to full-scale mutiny: they proposed replacing Moses with a new leader and returning to Egypt (14:4). The theological precision of their unbelief is striking. They did not merely doubt God's power; they reinterpreted His purpose as malice — 'Why is the LORD bringing us into this land, to fall by the sword?' (14:3). They looked at the same data that Caleb and Joshua would use to argue for faith and used it instead to argue for retreat. Moses and Aaron fell on their faces (14:5), a gesture of intercession and horror at what the congregation was doing. Caleb and Joshua tore their clothes (14:6) — the ritual mourning gesture — and gave the most compressed statement of faith in the chapter: 'The LORD is with us; do not fear them' (14:9). The congregation's response was to threaten stoning. The crisis was total: two faithful witnesses against six hundred thousand armed men demanding Egypt. At this precise moment, the glory of the LORD appeared at the tent of meeting (14:10)."
