          "body": "God's opening question to Moses is not a request for information but a formal indictment: 'How long will this people spurn Me? And how long will they not believe in Me, despite all the signs which I have performed in their midst?' (14:11). Two verbs carry the charge. *Naats* — to spurn, to treat with contempt — is a word for active disdain, not passive neglect. And *aman* — to believe, to trust, to treat as firm — is the root of the word *amen*. The indictment is that Israel has seen the signs (the ten plagues, the Exodus, the Red Sea, the manna, the water from the rock) and still refused to treat God as trustworthy. The aggravating clause is 'despite all the signs.' Sight without faith is the chapter's most devastating spiritual diagnosis, and it anticipates the New Testament's echo: Jesus marveled at unbelief in Nazareth (Mark 6:6) and warned that those who saw His signs and still would not believe faced a heavier judgment (John 12:37). God's initial proposal — to disinherit Israel and make of Moses a greater nation (14:12) — is structurally parallel to the golden calf episode (Exodus 32:10). In both cases the offer tests whether Moses himself will become a second Abraham rather than an intercessor."
